    "body": "@imagiMary yes, all keycard flows share the same closing policy logic which is set that user is able to close a popup only interacting with buttons displayed in the footer of that popup or upper right \"X\" (close) button if it is displayed. If \"X\" button is displayed user is able to close the popup pressing `Esc` key as well, otherwise only using buttons from the footer section.\r\n\r\nIf there is a request for the change we can change that, but we will still have some states in all those flows where we will disable any user's interactions with the popup or enable only the ones we want user to interact with.\r\n\r\nFor example when user runs the change password flow, the last step of that flow, if everything went well, will be a popup which cannot be closed anyhow (except if user close the app) and the only button which will be enabled is \"Restart app\" button, cause in such case we have to force user to restart the app cause the db is re-encypted and we cannot let user continue using it.\r\n\r\nAlso for example if user runs \"Setup a new Keycard with an existing account\" flow and migrating a profile keypair, in this screen the migrations is happening and notice that everything is disabled, so we don't allow user to do anything while that is ongoing:\r\n\r\n![a1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/86303051/222707869-5c796506-3de5-49b5-903a-a510095bc692.png)\r\n\r\nThen once migration is completed, we offer user only a single button enabled, so the only user actually can do at this step is to restart the app (no close popup, no anything else):\r\n\r\n![a2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/86303051/222708023-d973cb3b-f8df-49bc-ab7b-07186f29af56.png)\r\n",
